Test for statinarity (ADF)¶

ADF Statistic: -33.22928808685713
p-value: 0.0

Since the p-value is much smaller than 0.05, we can conclude that the Energy_Consumption time series is stationary. This means that the data does not require differencing, and you can directly proceed to time series modeling, such as ARIMA, without additional preprocessing for stationarity.

Smoothing & Moving Average¶

Rolling means (or moving averages) calculate the average of a specific window of time, sliding across the data. It’s a simple yet effective way to analyze trends and smooth fluctuations. Spot anomalies by comparing actual values to the rolling mean, which serves as a baseline.

Smoothing The Target variables¶

Exponential Smoothing is a time series forecasting method that assigns exponentially decreasing weights to older observations. It is particularly useful for capturing trends and seasonal patterns in your data. Manufacturing data, such as energy consumption or defect rates, can be noisy due to random variations. Exponential Smoothing helps filter out noise while retaining the underlying trend.
